---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import CaseStudySnapshot from "@/components/CaseStudySnapshot.astro"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import letterheadImg from "@/assets/projects/ncga-stationery/letterhead-house.png"
import envelopeImg from "@/assets/projects/ncga-stationery/envelope-editor.png"

const project = getProject("ncga-stationery-templates")!

const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [640, 960, 1280]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 768px) 960px, 100vw"

const snapshotItems = [
  {
    label: "Problem",
    value:
      "Repeat NCGA stationery for 170+ members; per-legislator files led to inconsistent spacing, colors, and correction rounds.",
  },
  {
    label: "Primary users",
    value:
      "In-house print shop staff producing legislator letterhead and envelopes.",
  },
  {
    label: "Design move",
    value:
      "One locked template structure with a governed LegislatorRecord, so staff edit only what production allows.",
  },
  {
    label: "Result",
    value:
      "Governed template tool with print-accurate preview and PDF export; fewer mistakes on repeat orders and cleaner handoff into single-pass mail merge.",
  },
]
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="NCGA Stationery Template System"
  description="A constrained template engine for North Carolina General Assembly stationery: one locked structure, governed variable data, and print-accurate preview for 170+ legislators."
  seoTitle="NCGA Stationery Template System · Information Architecture"
  seoDescription="Designing a constrained template engine for NCGA legislator letterhead and envelopes: LOCKED vs DATA-DRIVEN fields, print-accurate preview, and fewer production mistakes."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The North Carolina General Assembly print shop produces repeat stationery
    for more than 170 legislators, including business cards, letterhead, envelopes, and
    related materials. Each order carries the same formal brand requirements but
    different contact data, committee lists, and chamber-specific wording.
  </p>
  <p>
    I built a constrained template tool, not a document editor, that keeps seal
    placement, masthead type, grid, and margins locked while staff edit only the
    fields production allows. One <strong>LegislatorRecord</strong> is the single
    source of truth, poured into letterhead and envelope layouts with
    print-accurate preview and client-side PDF export. Those PDFs feed the same
    variable-data pipeline I use to merge base stationery with per-recipient
    address and body content in a single press run across all 170 members, replacing
    a second trip through the press on personalized mailings.
  </p>

  <CaseStudySnapshot items={snapshotItems} />

  <h2>The Friction in Production</h2>
  <p>
    Before the system, repeat orders relied on separate files per legislator.
    Small differences in spacing and ink color compounded across 170+ members.
    When a legislator updated a phone number or committee assignment, staff had
    to hunt the right file and hope the layout still matched shop standards.
  </p>
  <p>The production workflow needed to solve three practical problems:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Brand compliance.</strong> Seal, masthead, and typography had to stay
      fixed regardless of who edited the order.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Data variation.</strong> Names, addresses, committee lists, and chamber
      wording all changed, but the structure could not.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Repeat accuracy.</strong> The same legislator might reorder letterhead
      multiple times a session; each run had to match the last without reintroducing
      spacing or color drift.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <figure class="case-figure">
    <Picture
      src={letterheadImg}
      alt="Letterhead editor with a form sidebar and print-accurate preview of NCGA stationery."
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
    />
    <figcaption>
      Split-pane editor: governed fields on the left, locked template preview on
      the right. Sample data uses fictional legislator names.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>LOCKED vs DATA-DRIVEN</h2>
  <p>
    The core information architecture decision was explicit: everything the print
    shop is allowed to vary lives in a typed record; everything else is hardcoded
    into the template and never exposed in the form.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>LOCKED</strong> elements include the state seal, “North Carolina
    General Assembly” masthead, licensed typefaces, page grid, margins, and
    recycle mark geometry. <strong>DATA-DRIVEN</strong> fields include member
    name, chamber, office address, phone, committees, and ink color, with
    visibility toggles that hide sections on the letterhead without deleting the
    underlying data.
  </p>
  <p>
    My first instinct was to hand staff a Word or InDesign template they could
    edit freely. That approach failed quickly: font substitutions, nudged seal
    placement, and off-brand ink colors showed up on every correction round. A
    full WYSIWYG editor would have invited the same drift. The constrained form
    won because it maps one-to-one to what production actually allows.
  </p>

  <div class="template-flow" aria-label="Legislator record to output">
    <div class="template-flow__node">
      <span>Input</span>
      <strong>LegislatorRecord</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="template-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="template-flow__node template-flow__node--wide">
      <span>Locked template</span>
      <strong>Seal, masthead, grid, type</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="template-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="template-flow__node">
      <span>Output</span>
      <strong>Letterhead or envelope PDF</strong>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Same Record, Different Surfaces</h2>
  <p>
    Letterhead and envelopes share one data model but not one form. The
    letterhead editor exposes the full record plus visibility toggles for
    address, phone, and committees. The envelope editor uses a field subset: no
    phone or committees, and return addresses constrained to two NCGA buildings
    (Legislative Building or Legislative Office Building) with fixed ZIP codes
    rather than free text.
  </p>
  <p>
    Envelopes also omit the state seal, matching real production artwork, and
    explicitly defer recipient addresses to a downstream mail-merge pipeline.
    That boundary keeps the tool focused on return-address stationery staff
    produce in bulk, not one-off mailing lists.
  </p>

  <figure class="case-figure">
    <Picture
      src={envelopeImg}
      alt="Envelope editor with building picker and print-accurate envelope preview."
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
    />
    <figcaption>
      Envelope surface: building picker instead of free-text address, no seal,
      recipients added later by mail merge.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Print Fidelity as UX</h2>
  <p>
    The on-screen preview is sized in real inches and points so staff see what
    print will look like before exporting. Screen rendering uses DOM and Tailwind;
    PDF output uses a second renderer sharing the same business logic for
    chamber copy, ink colors, and visible committees. That split was deliberate:
    a screenshot export would not survive Acrobat; DOM alone cannot produce
    reliable print PDFs.
  </p>
  <p>
    Chamber selection drives both the masthead line and honorific automatically,
    so staff cannot accidentally pair “Senator” with House wording. Committee
    rows filter blank entries before preview and export, and long committee lists
    stress-test layout without breaking the locked grid.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    Standardizing on one structure with governed variable data reduced mistakes
    on repeat stationery orders. Staff no longer maintain parallel files that
    drift in spacing and color; edits stay inside the template rules production
    already enforces.
  </p>
  <p>
    This case study covers the letterhead and envelope editor slice of broader
    NCGA work. Related NCGA work includes a press-split calculator
    for job planning, the America 250 committee seal and branding, and
    high-volume production workflows, not shown here. What stuck with me is the
    same lesson as other workflow design: the hard part was deciding what staff
    are <em>not</em> allowed to change, not polishing what they can.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>

<style>
  .case-figure {
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }

  .case-figure :global(img) {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.375rem;
  }

  .case-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .template-flow {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }

  .template-flow__node {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.375rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--background) 96%, var(--muted));
  }

  .template-flow__node span {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    line-height: 1.2;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .template-flow__node strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
  }

  .template-flow__connector {
    width: 1px;
    height: 1.25rem;
    margin-left: 1.25rem;
    background: var(--border);
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .template-flow {
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 2rem minmax(0, 1.2fr) 2rem minmax(
          0,
          1fr
        );
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0;
    }

    .template-flow__connector {
      width: 100%;
      height: 1px;
      margin-left: 0;
    }
  }
</style>
